<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>What are the problems with polynomial interpolation for a large number of data set? How such problems are addressed? Explain with an example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Polynomial interpolation is a method of estimating the value of a function at a certain point based on the known values of the function at other points. One of the main problems with polynomial interpolation is that it can become unstable as the number of data points increases. This is because polynomial interpolation involves fitting a polynomial curve to the data points, and as the number of data points increases, the polynomial curve may become more complex and may not accurately represent the underlying function.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>One way to address this problem is to use a technique called regularization, which involves adding a penalty term to the polynomial interpolation equation to discourage overly complex solutions. This can help to reduce overfitting, which is when the polynomial curve fits the data points too closely and does not generalize well to new data.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Another method for addressing the problem of instability in polynomial interpolation is to use a different interpolation technique, such as spline interpolation or smoothing spline interpolation. These methods involve fitting a smooth curve to the data points rather than a polynomial curve, which can be more stable and accurate for large datasets.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>For example, consider a dataset with 50 data points that are evenly spaced along the x-axis. If we try to fit a polynomial curve to these data points, the resulting curve may be highly complex and may not accurately represent the underlying function. However, if we use spline interpolation or smoothing spline interpolation instead, we may obtain a smoother and more stable curve that is more representative of the underlying function.</p>
</div>
